## Field reference

| attribute | constraints |
|---|---|
| `name` | Optional. Up to 128 characters. Defaults to `""`. Not required to be unique. |
| `comment` | Optional. Free-form string (nullable). |
| `position` | Optional + computed integer `>= 1`. See **`position` semantics** below. |
| `action` | Optional. One of the `action` values below. Defaults to `accept`. |
| `session_types` | Optional set. Empty = Any. Items are `session_types` values below. |
| `resource_types` | Optional set. Empty = Any. Items are `resource_types` values below. |
| `location_ids` | Optional set of integers. Empty = Any. |
| `tag_ids` | Optional set of integers. Empty = Any. |
| `role_ids` | Optional set of integers. Empty = Any. |
| `command_acl_ids` | Optional set of integers referencing `mistershell_session_policy_acl` IDs. Empty = Any. |
| `notify` | Optional boolean. Defaults to `false`. |
| `log` | Optional boolean. Defaults to `false`. |
| `enabled` | Optional boolean. Defaults to `true`. |
| `hit_count` | Read-only runtime counter (number of matches). |
| `last_hit_at` | Read-only timestamp of the last match. |

### `action` values

| action | meaning |
|---|---|
| `accept` | Allow the matched session/command (the default). |
| `deny` | Block the matched session/command. |

### `session_types` values

A set; empty means **Any** session type. Order is irrelevant.

| session_type | meaning |
|---|---|
| `shell` | Shell (terminal) sessions. |
| `graphical` | Graphical (RDP/VNC-style) sessions. |

### `resource_types` values

A set; empty means **Any** resource type. Order is irrelevant. These are the
inventory resource-type strings; the complete set of valid values is:

| resource_type |
|---|
| `aws_account` |
| `azure_subscription` |
| `cisco_ios` |
| `cisco_iosxe` |
| `cisco_iosxe_sdwan` |
| `cisco_ise` |
| `cisco_nxos` |
| `cisco_vbond` |
| `cisco_vmanage` |
| `cisco_vsmart` |
| `database` |
| `generic_rdp` |
| `generic_ssh` |
| `infoblox_nios` |
| `kubernetes_cluster` |
| `linux` |
| `panos_ssh` |
| `windows` |

## `position` semantics

Rules form an ordered chain. `position` is a **declarative 1-based integer**
controlling evaluation order:

- **Lower `position` runs first** (higher priority).
- **Omit `position`** to append at the end — the server assigns `max + 10`. The
  assigned value is read back into state (Optional + Computed), so an omitted
  `position` does not produce a perpetual diff.
- **Assign distinct values** (the conventional `10, 20, 30, …` with gaps) for
  deterministic ordering. The backend does **not** enforce unique positions; two
  rules sharing a `position` break ties by `id` (creation order).
- The provider sets `position` directly on create and update; it **never** calls
  the backend's reorder endpoint. To reorder, simply change the `position` values.

## Notes

- **Read is via the list endpoint.** The backend exposes no GET-single route for
  rules, so the provider reads a rule by listing and filtering on `id`.
- **The last remaining rule cannot be deleted.** The backend refuses to delete the
  final rule (the chain is never empty); edit it instead of destroying it.
- **`hit_count` / `last_hit_at` are runtime telemetry.** They are read-only and
  do not trigger updates when they change.

